A useful approach I've seen (from the Nanny program developed in CMU's
Computer Science department) is to have a monitoring daemon, but in fact
to have two instances of the monitoring daemon running, each monitoring
the other as well as all the system processes.  When one instance
crashes, you have a reasonable chance that the other will re-start its
companion monitor.

		Craig

